SIMPLE: entertain
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Entertain
<hw>En`ter*tain"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Entertained</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Entertaining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>entretenir</ets>; <ets>entre</ets> between (L. <ets>inter</ets>) +
<ets>tenir</ets> to hold, L. <ets>tenere</ets>. See
<er>Tenable</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be at the charges of; to
take or keep in one's service; to maintain; to support; to harbor; to
keep.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 497 --></p>

<p><q>You, sir, I <qex>entertain</qex> for one of my hundred.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give hospitable reception and maintenance to; to
receive at one's board, or into one's house; to receive as a
guest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be not forgetful to <qex>entertain</qex> strangers; for thereby
some have <qex>entertained</qex> unawares.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. xiii.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To engage the attention of agreeably; to amuse with
that which makes the time pass pleasantly; to divert; <as>as, to
<ex>entertain</ex> friends with conversation, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The weary time she can not <qex>entertain</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To give reception to; to receive, in general; to
receive and take into consideration; to admit, treat, or make use of;
<as>as, to <ex>entertain</ex> a proposal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am not here going to <qex>entertain</qex> so large a theme as
the philosophy of Locke.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A rumor gained ground, -- and, however absurd, was
<qex>entertained</qex> by some very sensible people.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To meet or encounter, as an enemy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To keep, hold, or maintain in the mind with favor;
to keep in the mind; to harbor; to cherish; <as>as, to
<ex>entertain</ex> sentiments</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To lead on; to bring along; to introduce.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To baptize all nations, and <qex>entertain</qex> them into the
services institutions of the holy Jesus.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To amuse; divert; maintain. See
<er>Amuse</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Entertain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Entertain
<hw>En`ter*tain"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To receive, or
provide entertainment for, guests; <as>as, he <ex>entertains</ex>
generously</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Entertain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Entertain
<hw>En`ter*tain"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>entretien</ets>,
fr. <ets>entretenir</ets>.]</ety> <def>Entertainment.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>entertained</ent>⟦br⟧
